---
source: src/cli/mod.rs, src/output/mod.rs
assertion: MCP adapter manifest exposes CLI commands as tools without separate business logic
schema:
  response: ee.response.v1
  manifest: ee.mcp.manifest.v1
contracts:
  - mcp manifest lists all public CLI commands as MCP tools
  - ee mcp serve-stdio is the explicit CLI entrypoint for the stdio adapter
  - default ee mcp serve-stdio reports mcp_feature_disabled instead of starting an adapter
  - tools mirror CLI contract with ee_ prefix naming
  - responseEnvelope and errorEnvelope reference stable schemas
  - capabilities.resources and capabilities.prompts require mcp feature
  - capabilityGap reports mcp_feature_disabled when feature is off
  - adapter.transport is stdio (no HTTP in MCP path)
  - adapter.runtime is asupersync (no tokio in default tree)
  - adapter.businessLogic is cli_core_services (adapter only, no separate logic)
  - registry.commandSource and schemaSource are public manifests
  - protocolVersion tracks MCP protocol compatibility
  - default build has mcp feature disabled
  - feature-gated code behind cfg!(feature = "mcp")
feature_requirements:
  - mcp feature enables full MCP server functionality
  - default build omits mcp to avoid stdio adapter overhead
  - MCP adapter wraps CLI commands, does not add business logic
evidence:
  - McpCommand::Manifest
  - McpCommand::ServeStdio
  - render_mcp_manifest_json()
  - handle_mcp_serve_stdio()
  - MCP_MANIFEST_SCHEMA_V1
  - MCP_PROTOCOL_VERSION
  - MCP_FEATURE_DISABLED_DEGRADATION
  - COMMAND_MANIFEST
  - cfg!(feature = "mcp")
